{"title_page": "Bangalore Nagarathnamma", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{infobox person\n|name =Bangalore Nagarathnamma\n|image=File:Bangalore Nagarathnamma.jpg\n|image_size=150px\n|birth_date =3 November 1878\n|birth_place =Nanjangud, Karnataka\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|df=yes|1952|5|19|1878|11|3}}\n|occupation =carnatic singer\n}}\n\n'''Bangalore Nagarathnamma''' (3 November 1878&nbsp;\u2013 19 May 1952)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eemaata.com/em/issues/200711/1166.html|title=\u0c35\u0c3f\u0c26\u0c4d\u0c2f\u0c3e\u0c38\u0c41\u0c02\u0c26\u0c30\u0c3f \u2013 \u0c08\u0c2e\u0c3e\u0c1f|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> was an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] singer, cultural activist, scholar, and courtesan.{{sfn|Ramamirthammal|Kannabiran|Kannabiran|2003|p=34}} A descendant of courtesans, she was also a patron of the arts and a historian.{{sfn|Chandra|2014|p=165}} Nagarathnamma built a temple over the [[samadhi]] of the Carnatic singer [[Tyagaraja]] at [[Thiruvaiyaru]] and helped establish the [[Tyagaraja Aradhana]] festival in his memory.{{sfn|C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation|1980|p=1}} Within a male dominated festival, she was the feminist aggressive enough to ensure that women artists were given equality to participate in it.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She \"was among the last practitioners of the [[devadasi]] tradition in India,\"{{sfn|McGonigal|2010|p=76}} and the first president of the Association of the Devadasis of Madras Presidency. She also edited and published books on poetry and anthologies.\n\n==Early life==\nNagarathnamma was born in 1878 to Puttu Lakshmi and Vakil Subba Rao,{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} in [[Nanjangud]]. Puttu Lakshmi's ancestors served as singers and musicians in the court of [[Mysore kingdom|Mysore]].<ref name=Venkataraman>{{Cite web|last=Venkataraman|first=Rajagopalan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Carnatic-musics-first-feminist-from-Bengaluru/articleshow/45755135.cms|title=Carnatic music's first feminist, from Bengaluru|date=5 January 2015|work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=Shriram>{{cite news|last=Sriram|first=V|authorlink=V. Sriram|title=A shrine built by Nagarathnamma|work=[[The Hindu]]|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article2795704.ece|date=12 January 2012}}</ref> Abandoned by Subba Rao, she found refuge under Shastri, a Sanskrit scholar in the court of the Mysore Maharaja. He educated Nagarathnamma in [[Sanskrit]] and music, and she was initiated in [[devadasi]] at the age of five.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} However, Shastri also abandoned Nagarathnamma who soon left Mysore and found protection under her uncle, Venkitaswamy Appa, a violinist by profession. Nagarthnamma continued her studies and learned [[Kannada]], [[English language|English]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]], also becoming proficient in music and dance.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} She was trained in [[Carnatic music]] by Munuswamappa in the 'shishya-parampara' (tradition of the student teacher learning process), on the process set by Thyagaraja.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She was able to make her first stage appearance before a learned audience as a violinist and dancer at the age of 15.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}}\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Mukunda Mala stotra by Bengaluru Nagaratnamma.ogg|thumb|Mukunda Mala stotra by Bengaluru Nagaratnamma]]\nNagarathnamma became a singer early in her life and emerged as one of the best Carnatic singers of her time. She sang in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]].<ref name=Shriram/> Her special musical forte included [[Harikatha]]. Her talent in dance attracted the attention of the Mysore ruler [[Jayachamarajendra Wodeyar]] who, impressed with her talent, made her the [[Asthana Vidushi]] (court dancer) in Mysore. Following the death of the ruler, she moved to [[Bangalore]]. She attained popularity in Bangalore not only in music but also in dance.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She was also patronized by many other royal houses such as those of [[Travancore]], [[Bobbili]], and [[Vijayanagaram]]. [[Narahari Rao]], a judge in the [[High Court of Mysore]], was one of Nagarathnamma's patrons and he suggested to her to move to Madras (now known as [[Chennai]]) to further her career as a musician and dancer. She shifted to there as it was considered the \"Mecca of Carnatic music\" and her musical talent was further developed. Here, she specifically identified herself as Bangalore Nagarathnamma.<ref name=Venkataraman/>\n\nThe patronage she received from Justice Narahari Rao made her famous as a \"concert artist\" in Madras. As promoter of Tyagaraja Aradhana, she was the \"first female artist to pay income tax\" in Madras, India.{{sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=xvii}}\n\n==Thyagaraja memorial and Aradhana==\n[[File:Marble notice board at ashram of singer Tyagaraja at Thiruvaiyaru.jpg|right|thumb|Marble notice board at ashram of singer Tyagaraja at Thiruvaiyaru]]\nAccording to Nagarathnamma, she was directed in a dream to build a memorial in honour of [[Thyagaraja]] and create a platform for perpetuating Carnatic music. Following this, she turned to an [[ascetic]] way of life and donated all her earnings to this cause.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=17}}\n\nWhile in Madras, Nagarathnamma was informed by her guru, [[Bidaram Krishnappa]], of the dilapidated status of the [[samadhi]] or tomb of saint Thyagaraja.<ref name=Venkataraman/> Bidaram Krishnappa's disciples, Krishna Bhagavatar and Sundara Bhagavatar, had erected a small edifice made of marble in 1903 and held annual music festivals in honour of Thyagaraja thereafter.<ref name=Shriram/> Within a few years, a feud had erupted among people interested in honouring the saint, and two rival groups were holding two rival concerts at the saint's samadhi. Upkeep of the tiny ediface had suffered and it had quickly fallen into dilapidation. This prompted Nagarathnamma to take steps to restore the samadhi and convert it into a memorial in honour of the Thyagaraja. She acquired the land where Thyagaraja's samadhi was located and built a larger ediface embodying a temple in his honour with her own financial resources. She arranged for an idol of sri Thyagaraja to be installed and consecrated by Brahmin priests and for prayers to be offered daily. The Thyagaraja Temple thus constructed was consecrated in 1921.\n\nAt that time, the music festival held at this location was male-dominated for the simple reason that in thosen days, decent woman would never sing or dance, and these skills were strictly the preserve of the courtesan and the devadasi, the two types of prostitutes found in south India at that time. The idea of one or more prostitutes singing and participating in the annual functions of the shrine was anathema to society, and the rival performing groups therefore prevented Nagarathnamma from participating in the festival, even though she had paid for the renovation and she said that she would not sing or dance like a courtesan, but would only recite [[Harikatha]] in front of the deity. Nevertheless, she was refused. She took this as a challenge and started organizing a parallel music festival at the back of the saint's temple.<ref name=Venkataraman/> Her group was named \"Pengal Katchi\" (women's group), and the Aradhana organized by her was held concurrently with the one organized by the male centric groups of the music festival, known as the \"Periya Katchi\" or \"major group\".<ref name=Shriram/> Eventually, in 1941, her activism paid off, and the opposing groups involved with the festival merged into a single entity, allowing both men and women to sing in the festival.<ref name=Venkataraman/>\n\nThis music festival has become renowned as one of the most popular musical event in [[South India]].{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=17}} This tradition of women musicians' participation at the annual festival, known popularly as the \"[[Thyagaraja Aradhana]]\", along with male musicians, has continued over the years.<ref name=Venkataraman/> In 1927, Nagarathnamma and other devadasis established the Association of the Devadasis of Madras Presidency; she was elected its first president.{{sfn|Muthiah|2011|p=479}}\n\n==Literary pursuits==\nAs an erudite and scholarly person, Nagarathnamma dabbled in editing and publishing books on [[poetry]] and [[anthologies]]. She was a [[linguist]] who held religious discourses not only in Kannada, her mother tongue, but also in other languages such as Telugu, Tamil and Sanskrit. During her foray into [[literature]], she came across an old poem called the ''[[Radhika Santawanam]]'' (Appeasing Radhika), which she found inadequately covered vis-a-vis the original version written by [[Muddupalani]], a courtesan herself,{{sfn|Chandra|2014|p=165}} in Telugu verses. This was a book which [[Paidipati Venkatanarasu]] had edited based on the ready to print version, which [[Charles Phillip Brown]], an eminent scholar in Telugu, had prepared and deposited in the [[Oriental Research Institute & Manuscripts Library|Oriental Manuscripts Library]] in 1855.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} However, Venkatanarasu, an associate of Brown, had printed an annotated version in 1887 (reprinted in 1907),{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} but had deliberately dropped a few erotic verses and also the prologue from the original version as he had considered them inappropriate to the then prevailing social norms. The prologue which he had deleted was related to the devadasi tradition that had been adopted by Nagarathnamma's mother and grandmother. This exclusion was particularly disliked by Nagarthnamma and she made efforts to get the original version written on palm leaves. Once she found the original version, she reedited the ''Radhika Santawanam'', which fully conformed to the palm leaf manuscript version. In 1910,{{sfn|Kramarae|Spender|2000|p=1278}} she published this book with a preface in which she noted that she had read and reread the poetic verses of the book several times for its aesthetic quality. The book, published 150 years after the original manuscript was written by Muddupalani in Telugu, was reviewed by [[Kandukuri Veeresalingam]], who, though a supporter of women's causes, attacked some of the erotic contents of the book as totally \"inappropriate for women to hear let alone be uttered from a woman's mouth.\"{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} Nagarathnamma strongly defended her version of the book and counterattacked saying that there was very much more  titillating content included in the book titled ''Vaijayantivilasam'', which the critic (Veeresalingam) had reviewed and accepted for printing. She protested against this double standard and wondered \"Does the question of propriety and embarrassment apply only in the case of women and not men\".{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=19}}\n\nMuddupalani's ''Radhika Santawanam'', edited by Nagarathnamma, was published but received criticism, with one Telugu magazine even noting that \"a prostitute had composed the book and another prostitute had edited it.\"{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=20}} Following the adverse reaction to the book, it was banned. However, with the intervention by Raja Venkatagiri the issue was \"soft-pedaled\". It was alleged that it was a vindictive action by the Veerasilingham lobby, as books with much more  suggestive content had been published. However, after India attained [[Independence of India|independence]] the ban on the book was lifted by [[Tanguturi Prakasam]], the then Chief Minister of Madras, with a comment that \"he was restoring a few pearls to the necklace of [[Telugu literature]]\".{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=20}}\n\n==Death==\nNagarathnamma died in 1952 at the age of 74; a memorial in her honour was erected next to Thyagaraja's samadhi.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=21}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation|title=Voice of Samanvaya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ols8AAAAMAAJ|year=1980|publisher=C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Chandra|first=Vikram|title=Geek Sublime: The Beauty of Code, the Code of Beauty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-4eBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT165|date=2 September 2014|publisher=Graywolf Press|isbn=978-1-55597-326-1}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Kramarae|first1=Cheris|last2=Spender|first2=Dale|title=Routledge International Encyclopaedia of Women 4 Volume Set: Global Women's Issues and Knowledge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QAOUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1278|date=27 December 2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-96315-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McGonigal|first=Mike|title=Yeti 9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6vbcTgH2y_kC&pg=PA76|date=5 April 2010|publisher=Verse Chorus Press|isbn=978-0-9788786-9-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Muthiah|first=S|title=Madras Miscellany|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QHtZG8beGy4C&pg=PT479|year=2011|publisher=Westland|isbn=978-93-80032-84-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pa\u1e37ani|first=Muddu|title=The Appeasement of Radhika|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KvNR1V6hKJAC&pg=PR21|year=2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341743-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Ramamirthammal|first1=Muvalar|last2=Kannabiran|first2=Kalpana|last3=Kannabiran|first3=Vasantha|title=Muvalur Ramamirthammal's Web of Deceit: Devadasi Reform in Colonial India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-kSUx6Xbq1QC&pg=PA34|year=2003|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-81-86706-63-3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite book|title=The Devadasi and the Saint: The Life and Times of Bangalore Nagarathnamma|year=2007|publisher=East-West Books|place=Chennai|first=V.|last=Sriram|authorlink=V. Sriram}}\nKapile Haridalu kadalige \u0c95\u0caa\u0cbf\u0cb2\u0cc6 \u0cb9\u0cb0\u0cbf\u0ca6\u0cb3\u0cc1 \u0c95\u0ca1\u0cb2\u0cbf\u0c97\u0cc6 , a novel written by prof.Maleyuru Guruswamy on the life of Bengaluru Nagarathnamma ...\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bangalore Nagarathnamma}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nagarathnamma, Bangalore}}\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Singers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women editors]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Indian women linguists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian linguists]]\n[[Category:Indian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Indian courtesans]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Businesswomen from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Female Carnatic singers]]\n[[Category:Carnatic singers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Writers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women social scientists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian educators]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women publishers]]\n[[Category:20th-century publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:19th-century publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian linguists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Kannada-language journalists]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian social scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian social scientists]]\n[[Category:Women educators from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Educators from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian businesswomen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesswomen]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{infobox person\n|name =Bangalore Nagarathnamma\n|image=File:Bangalore Nagarathnamma.jpg\n|image_size=150px\n|birth_date =3 November 1878\n|birth_place =Nanjangud, Karnataka\n|death_date ={{Death date and age|df=yes|1952|5|19|1878|11|3}}\n|occupation =carnatic singer\n}}\n\n'''Bangalore Nagarathnamma''' (3 November 1878&nbsp;\u2013 19 May 1952)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eemaata.com/em/issues/200711/1166.html|title=\u0c35\u0c3f\u0c26\u0c4d\u0c2f\u0c3e\u0c38\u0c41\u0c02\u0c26\u0c30\u0c3f \u2013 \u0c08\u0c2e\u0c3e\u0c1f|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> was an [[Indian people|Indian]] [[Carnatic music|Carnatic]] singer, cultural activist, scholar, and courtesan.{{sfn|Ramamirthammal|Kannabiran|Kannabiran|2003|p=34}} A descendant of courtesans, she was also a patron of the arts and a historian.{{sfn|Chandra|2014|p=165}} Nagarathnamma built a temple over the [[samadhi]] of the Carnatic singer [[Tyagaraja]] at [[Thiruvaiyaru]] and helped establish the [[Tyagaraja Aradhana]] festival in his memory.{{sfn|C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation|1980|p=1}} Within a male dominated festival, she was the feminist aggressive enough to ensure that women artists were given equality to participate in it.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She \"was among the last practitioners of the [[devadasi]] tradition in India,\"{{sfn|McGonigal|2010|p=76}} and the first president of the Association of the Devadasis of Madras Presidency. She also edited and published books on poetry and anthologies.\n\n==Early life==\nNagarathnamma was born in 1878 to Puttu Lakshmi and Vakil Subba Rao,{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} in [[Nanjangud]]. Puttu Lakshmi's ancestors served as singers and musicians in the court of [[Mysore kingdom|Mysore]].<ref name=Venkataraman>{{Cite web|last=Venkataraman|first=Rajagopalan|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Carnatic-musics-first-feminist-from-Bengaluru/articleshow/45755135.cms|title=Carnatic music's first feminist, from Bengaluru|date=5 January 2015|work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=Shriram>{{cite news|last=Sriram|first=V|authorlink=V. Sriram|title=A shrine built by Nagarathnamma|work=[[The Hindu]]|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/music/article2795704.ece|date=12 January 2012}}</ref> Abandoned by Subba Rao, she found refuge under Shastri, a Sanskrit scholar in the court of the Mysore Maharaja. He educated Nagarathnamma in [[Sanskrit]] and music, and she was initiated in [[devadasi]] at the age of five.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} However, Shastri also abandoned Nagarathnamma who soon left Mysore and found protection under her uncle, Venkitaswamy Appa, a violinist by profession. Nagarthnamma continued her studies and learned [[Kannada]], [[English language|English]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]], also becoming proficient in music and dance.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}} She was trained in [[Carnatic music]] by Munuswamappa in the 'shishya-parampara' (tradition of the student teacher learning process), on the process set by Thyagaraja.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She was able to make her first stage appearance before a learned audience as a violinist and dancer at the age of 15.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=16}}\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Mukunda Mala stotra by Bengaluru Nagaratnamma.ogg|thumb|Mukunda Mala stotra by Bengaluru Nagaratnamma]]\nNagarathnamma became a singer early in her life and emerged as one of the best Carnatic singers of her time. She sang in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]].<ref name=Shriram/> Her special musical forte included [[Harikatha]]. Her talent in dance attracted the attention of the Mysore ruler [[Jayachamarajendra Wodeyar]] who, impressed with her talent, made her the [[Asthana Vidushi]] (court dancer) in Mysore. Following the death of the ruler, she moved to [[Bangalore]]. She attained popularity in Bangalore not only in music but also in dance.<ref name=Venkataraman/> She was also patronized by many other royal houses such as those of [[Travancore]], [[Bobbili]], and [[Vijayanagaram]]. [[Narahari Rao]], a judge in the [[High Court of Mysore]], was one of Nagarathnamma's patrons and he suggested to her to move to Madras (now known as [[Chennai]]) to further her career as a musician and dancer. She shifted to there as it was considered the \"Mecca of Carnatic music\" and her musical talent was further developed. Here, she specifically identified herself as Bangalore Nagarathnamma.<ref name=Venkataraman/>\n\nThe patronage she received from Justice Narahari Rao made her famous as a \"concert artist\" in Madras. As promoter of Tyagaraja Aradhana, she was the \"first female artist to pay income tax\" in Madras, India.{{sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=xvii}}\n\n==Thyagaraja memorial and Aradhana==\n[[File:Marble notice board at ashram of singer Tyagaraja at Thiruvaiyaru.jpg|right|thumb|Marble notice board at ashram of singer Tyagaraja at Thiruvaiyaru]]\nAccording to Nagarathnamma, she was directed in a dream to build a memorial in honour of [[Thyagaraja]] and create a platform for perpetuating Carnatic music. Following this, she turned to an [[ascetic]] way of life and donated all her earnings to this cause.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=17}}\n\nWhile in Madras, Nagarathnamma was informed by her guru, [[Bidaram Krishnappa]], of the dilapidated status of the [[samadhi]] or tomb of saint Thyagaraja.<ref name=Venkataraman/> Bidaram Krishnappa's disciples, Krishna Bhagavatar and Sundara Bhagavatar, had erected a small edifice made of marble in 1903 and held annual music festivals in honour of Thyagaraja thereafter.<ref name=Shriram/> Within a few years, a feud had erupted among people interested in honouring the saint, and two rival groups were holding two rival concerts at the saint's samadhi. Upkeep of the tiny ediface had suffered and it had quickly fallen into dilapidation. This prompted Nagarathnamma to take steps to restore the samadhi and convert it into a memorial in honour of the Thyagaraja. She acquired the land where Thyagaraja's samadhi was located and built a larger ediface embodying a temple in his honour with her own financial resources. She arranged for an idol of sri Thyagaraja to be installed and consecrated by Brahmin priests and for prayers to be offered daily. The Thyagaraja Temple thus constructed was consecrated in 1921.\n\nAt that time, the music festival held at this location was male-dominated for the simple reason that in thosen days, decent woman would never sing or dance, and these skills were strictly the preserve of the courtesan and the devadasi, the two types of prostutites found in south India at that time. The idea of one or more prostitutes singing and participating in the annual functions of the shrine was anathema to society, and the rival performing groups therefore prevented Nagarathnamma from participating in the festival, even though she had paid for the renovation and she said that she would not sing or dance like a courtesan, but would only recite [[Harikatha]] in front of the deity. Nevertheless she was refused. She took this as a challenge and started organizing a parallel music festival at the back of the saint's temple.<ref name=Venkataraman/> Her group was named \"Pengal Katchi\" (women's group), and the Aradhana organized by her was held concurrently with the one organized by the male centric groups of the music festival, known as the \"Periya Katchi\" or \"major group\".<ref name=Shriram/> Eventually, in 1941, her activism paid off, and the opposing groups involved with the festival merged into a single entity, allowing both men and women to sing in the festival.<ref name=Venkataraman/>\n\nThis music festival has become renowned as one of the most popular musical event in [[South India]].{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=17}} This tradition of women musicians' participation at the annual festival, known popularly as the \"[[Thyagaraja Aradhana]]\", along with male musicians, has continued over the years.<ref name=Venkataraman/> In 1927, Nagarathnamma and other devadasis established the Association of the Devadasis of Madras Presidency; she was elected its first president.{{sfn|Muthiah|2011|p=479}}\n\n==Literary pursuits==\nAs an erudite and scholarly person, Nagarathnamma dabbled in editing and publishing books on [[poetry]] and [[anthologies]]. She was a [[linguist]] who held religious discourses not only in Kannada, her mother tongue, but also in other languages such as Telugu, Tamil and Sanskrit. During her foray into [[literature]], she came across an old poem called the ''[[Radhika Santawanam]]'' (Appeasing Radhika), which she found inadequately covered vis-a-vis the original version written by [[Muddupalani]], a courtesan herself,{{sfn|Chandra|2014|p=165}} in Telugu verses. This was a book which [[Paidipati Venkatanarasu]] had edited based on the ready to print version, which [[Charles Phillip Brown]], an eminent scholar in Telugu, had prepared and deposited in the [[Oriental Research Institute & Manuscripts Library|Oriental Manuscripts Library]] in 1855.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} However, Venkatanarasu, an associate of Brown, had printed an annotated version in 1887 (reprinted in 1907),{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} but had deliberately dropped a few erotic verses and also the prologue from the original version as he had considered them inappropriate to the then prevailing social norms. The prologue which he had deleted was related to the devadasi tradition that had been adopted by Nagarathnamma's mother and grandmother. This exclusion was particularly disliked by Nagarthnamma and she made efforts to get the original version written on palm leaves. Once she found the original version, she reedited the ''Radhika Santawanam'', which fully conformed to the palm leaf manuscript version. In 1910,{{sfn|Kramarae|Spender|2000|p=1278}} she published this book with a preface in which she noted that she had read and reread the poetic verses of the book several times for its aesthetic quality. The book, published 150 years after the original manuscript was written by Muddupalani in Telugu, was reviewed by [[Kandukuri Veeresalingam]], who, though a supporter of women's causes, attacked some of the erotic contents of the book as totally \"inappropriate for women to hear let alone be uttered from a woman's mouth.\"{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=18}} Nagarathnamma strongly defended her version of the book and counterattacked saying that there was very much more  titillating content included in the book titled ''Vaijayantivilasam'', which the critic (Veeresalingam) had reviewed and accepted for printing. She protested against this double standard and wondered \"Does the question of propriety and embarrassment apply only in the case of women and not men\".{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=19}}\n\nMuddupalani's ''Radhika Santawanam'', edited by Nagarathnamma, was published but received criticism, with one Telugu magazine even noting that \"a prostitute had composed the book and another prostitute had edited it.\"{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=20}} Following the adverse reaction to the book, it was banned. However, with the intervention by Raja Venkatagiri the issue was \"soft-pedaled\". It was alleged that it was a vindictive action by the Veerasilingham lobby, as books with much more  suggestive content had been published. However, after India attained [[Independence of India|independence]] the ban on the book was lifted by [[Tanguturi Prakasam]], the then Chief Minister of Madras, with a comment that \"he was restoring a few pearls to the necklace of [[Telugu literature]]\".{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=20}}\n\n==Death==\nNagarathnamma died in 1952 at the age of 74; a memorial in her honour was erected next to Thyagaraja's samadhi.{{Sfn|Pa\u1e37ani|2011|p=21}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|author=C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation|title=Voice of Samanvaya|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ols8AAAAMAAJ|year=1980|publisher=C. P. Ramaswami Aiyar Foundation}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Chandra|first=Vikram|title=Geek Sublime: The Beauty of Code, the Code of Beauty|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-4eBAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT165|date=2 September 2014|publisher=Graywolf Press|isbn=978-1-55597-326-1}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Kramarae|first1=Cheris|last2=Spender|first2=Dale|title=Routledge International Encyclopaedia of Women 4 Volume Set: Global Women's Issues and Knowledge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QAOUAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA1278|date=27 December 2000|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-96315-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=McGonigal|first=Mike|title=Yeti 9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6vbcTgH2y_kC&pg=PA76|date=5 April 2010|publisher=Verse Chorus Press|isbn=978-0-9788786-9-6}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Muthiah|first=S|title=Madras Miscellany|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QHtZG8beGy4C&pg=PT479|year=2011|publisher=Westland|isbn=978-93-80032-84-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pa\u1e37ani|first=Muddu|title=The Appeasement of Radhika|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KvNR1V6hKJAC&pg=PR21|year=2011|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-341743-9|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|last1=Ramamirthammal|first1=Muvalar|last2=Kannabiran|first2=Kalpana|last3=Kannabiran|first3=Vasantha|title=Muvalur Ramamirthammal's Web of Deceit: Devadasi Reform in Colonial India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-kSUx6Xbq1QC&pg=PA34|year=2003|publisher=Zubaan|isbn=978-81-86706-63-3}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* {{cite book|title=The Devadasi and the Saint: The Life and Times of Bangalore Nagarathnamma|year=2007|publisher=East-West Books|place=Chennai|first=V.|last=Sriram|authorlink=V. Sriram}}\nKapile Haridalu kadalige \u0c95\u0caa\u0cbf\u0cb2\u0cc6 \u0cb9\u0cb0\u0cbf\u0ca6\u0cb3\u0cc1 \u0c95\u0ca1\u0cb2\u0cbf\u0c97\u0cc6 , a novel written by prof.Maleyuru Guruswamy on the life of Bengaluru Nagarathnamma ...\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bangalore Nagarathnamma}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nagarathnamma, Bangalore}}\n[[Category:1878 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Singers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women editors]]\n[[Category:Indian editors]]\n[[Category:Indian women linguists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian linguists]]\n[[Category:Indian publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:Indian courtesans]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Businesswomen from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian singers]]\n[[Category:Female Carnatic singers]]\n[[Category:Carnatic singers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Writers from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Indian women social scientists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian educators]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women publishers]]\n[[Category:20th-century publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:19th-century publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian linguists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Kannada-language journalists]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Scholars from Bangalore]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian women singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian social scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian social scientists]]\n[[Category:Women educators from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Educators from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Women musicians from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:19th-century Indian businesswomen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesswomen]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe