{"title_page": "People Need Love", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = People Need Love/[[En karusell|Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)]]\"\n| cover      = People Need Love Merry Go Round.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Standard European artwork ''(One of Swedish releases pictured)''\n| type       = Single\n| artist     = [[ABBA]] (known at the time as 'Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid')\n| album      = [[Ring Ring (album)|Ring Ring]]\n| B-side     = [[En karusell|Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)]]\n| released   = June 1, 1972\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = March 29, 1972<br />Metronome studios, [[Stockholm]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Europop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 2:48\n| label      = [[Polar Music]]\n| writer     = [[Benny Andersson]]<br />[[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n| producer   = Benny Andersson<br />Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[He Is Your Brother]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|pO7ubf4h8sk|\"\"People Need Love\"}} }}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        =\n | file        = People Need Love - ABBA.ogg\n | description = \"People Need Love\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''People Need Love'''\" is the debut single recorded in March 1972 by Swedish pop group [[ABBA]], at the time known as 'Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid'. The song was on the group's first album, ''[[Ring Ring (album)|Ring Ring]]'', released in 1973.\n\n==Track listing==\n\n# A. \"People Need Love\" - 2:45\n# B. \"Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)\" - 3:24\n\n==The song==\nAs the majority of ABBA songs were, \"People Need Love\" was written and composed by the two male band members, [[Benny Andersson]] & [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]. It was engineered by [[Michael Tretow]] who aimed to create a [[Phil Spector]]-like [[Wall of Sound|wall of sound]] on the recording.\n\nAlthough their debut album did not bring them to global attention, it follows some standards of ABBA's style. The [[ballad]] is about what people can give each other to make their lives easier and create a better world.\n\n==Reception==\nThe basic aim of the \"People Need Love\" single was not to promote the quartet, since all four individuals had other commitments and did not have the time to form a permanent group (an example of this is the crediting; the single in most of the territories is credited to \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid\"), but to promote the \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny\" duo, which was the singing and songwriting partnership of the two men. The women were simply guesting on the new \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny\" single. However, the very positive audience reaction was unexpected.\n\n\"People Need Love\" made the Top 20 of the combined Swedish singles and albums chart, and reached No. 3 on the popular Swedish radio chart show, ''Tio i topp'' (The Top Ten). It was the foursome's first charting record in the [[United States]], where it peaked at No. 114 on the [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] singles chart and No. 117 on [[Record World]] singles chart. The [[Playboy Records]] [[United States|U.S.]] release was credited to \"Bjorn & Benny (with Svenska Flicka)\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/p50014 |title=Bj\u00f6rn and Benny (With Svenska Flicka) - People Need Love / Merry-Go-Round - Playboy - USA - P 50014 |website=45cat.com |date=1972-09-16 |accessdate=2016-10-07}}</ref> and according to ABBA's manager [[Stig Anderson]], could have been a much bigger American hit, if not for the limited distribution resources of the label that was unable to meet the demand from retailers and radio programmers.\n\nAt the time of the single's release, the ''Ring Ring'' album had not been planned, since there was no intention to form a permanent group. However, the song was included on the album the following year. Although recorded earlier than most of the album, it can retroactively be considered the lead single from ''Ring Ring''.\n\nIn the Netherlands and Belgium the single had its release in August 1973 as the follow-up to the highly successful single ''Ring Ring''. It however performed rather badly, reaching just no. 47 on the Radio Noordzee Top 50 from the Dutch service of [[Radio North Sea International]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.planet.nl/~elber875/RNITop50_1973_09_15.html |title=Radio Noordzee Top 50 15 september 1973 |website=http://home.planet.nl |date=1973-09-15 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1972)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Tio i Topp\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Swedish Combined Singles/Albums Chart \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Cashbox Singles Chart - U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|114\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Record World Singles Chart - U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|117\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\nA Swedish country band called Nashville Train (which included some of ABBA's own backing band members) covered the song in 1977 on their album ''ABBA Our Way'', released on the Polar Music label in Sweden.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|abba|people-need-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pO7ubf4h8sk 1972 television appearance] at YouTube\n\n{{ABBA songs}}\n\n[[Category:ABBA songs]]\n[[Category:1972 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1972 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Benny Andersson and Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n[[Category:Playboy Records singles]]\n[[Category:Polar Music singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = People Need Love/[[En karusell|Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)]]\"\n| cover      = People Need Love Merry Go Round.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Standard European artwork ''(One of Swedish releases pictured)''\n| type       = Single\n| artist     = [[ABBA]] (known at the time as 'Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid')\n| album      = [[Ring Ring (album)|Ring Ring]]\n| B-side     = [[En karusell|Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)]]\n| released   = June 1, 1972\n| format     = [[Single (music)|7\" single]]\n| recorded   = March 29, 1972<br />Metronome studios, [[Stockholm]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Europop]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| length     = 2:48\n| label      = [[Polar Music]]\n| writer     = [[Benny Andersson]]<br />[[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n| producer   = Benny Andersson<br />Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[He Is Your Brother]]\n| next_year  = 1972\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|pO7ubf4h8sk|\"\"People Need Love\"}} }}\n{{Audio sample\n | type        =\n | file        = People Need Love - ABBA.ogg\n | description = \"People Need Love\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''People Need Love'''\" is the debut single recorded in March 1972 by Swedish pop group [[ABBA]], at the time known as 'Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid'. The song was on the group's first album, ''[[Ring Ring (album)|Ring Ring]]'', released in 1973.\n\n==Track listing==\n\n# A. \"People Need Love\" - 2:45\n# B. \"Merry-Go-Round (En karusell)\" - 3:24\n\n==The song==\nAs the majority of ABBA songs were, \"People Need Love\" was written and composed by the two male band members, [[Benny Andersson]] & [[Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]. It was engineered by [[Michael Tretow]] who aimed to create a [[Phil Spector]]-like [[Wall of Sound|wall of sound]] on the recording.\n\nAlthough their debut album did not bring them to global attention, it follows some standards of ABBA's style. The [[ballad]] is about what people can give each other to make their lives easier and create a better world.\n\n==Reception==\nThe basic aim of the \"People Need Love\" single was not to promote the quartet, since all four individuals had other commitments and did not have the time to form a permanent group (an example of this is the crediting; the single in most of the territories is credited to \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny, Agnetha & Anni-Frid\"), but to promote the \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny\" duo, which was the singing and songwriting partnership of the two men. The women were simply guesting on the new \"Bj\u00f6rn & Benny\" single. However, the very positive audience reaction was unexpected.\n\n\"People Need Love\" made the Top 20 of the combined Swedish singles and albums chart, and reached No. 3 on the popular Swedish radio chart show, ''Tio i topp'' (The Top Ten). It was the foursome's first charting record in the [[United States]], where it peaked at No. 114 on the [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]] singles chart and No. 117 on [[Record World]] singles chart. The [[Playboy Records]] [[United States|U.S.]] release was credited to \"Bjorn & Benny (with Svenska Flicka)\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45cat.com/record/p50014 |title=Bj\u00f6rn and Benny (With Svenska Flicka) - People Need Love / Merry-Go-Round - Playboy - USA - P 50014 |website=45cat.com |date=1972-09-16 |accessdate=2016-10-07}}</ref> and according to ABBA's manager [[Stig Anderson]], could have been a much bigger American hit, if not for the limited distribution resources of the label that was unable to meet the demand from retailers and radio programmers.\n\nAt the time of the single's release, the ''Ring Ring'' album had not been planned, since there was no intention to form a permanent group. However, the song was included on the album the following year. Although recorded earlier than most of the album, it can retroactively be considered the lead single from ''Ring Ring''.\n\nIn the Netherlands and Belgium the single had its release in August 1973 as the follow-up to the highly successfull single ''Ring Ring''. It however performed rather badly, reaching just no. 47 on the Radio Noordzee Top 50 from the Dutch service of [[Radio North Sea International]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.planet.nl/~elber875/RNITop50_1973_09_15.html |title=Radio Noordzee Top 50 15 september 1973 |website=http://home.planet.nl |date=1973-09-15 |accessdate=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n==Chart positions==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1972)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Tio i Topp\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Swedish Combined Singles/Albums Chart \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|17\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Cashbox Singles Chart - U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|114\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Record World Singles Chart - U.S.\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|117\n|}\n\n==Cover versions==\nA Swedish country band called Nashville Train (which included some of ABBA's own backing band members) covered the song in 1977 on their album ''ABBA Our Way'', released on the Polar Music label in Sweden.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|abba|people-need-love}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pO7ubf4h8sk 1972 television appearance] at YouTube\n\n{{ABBA songs}}\n\n[[Category:ABBA songs]]\n[[Category:1972 debut singles]]\n[[Category:1972 songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Benny Andersson and Bj\u00f6rn Ulvaeus]]\n[[Category:Playboy Records singles]]\n[[Category:Polar Music singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReception:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: full \u2192 ful", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People_Need_Love"}
{"title_page": "1884 Calgary municipal election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 1884 Calgary municipal election\n| country           = Calgary\n| type              = Municipal\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = <nowiki>None</nowiki>\n| previous_year     = <nowiki>None</nowiki>\n| next_election     = January 1886 Calgary municipal election\n| next_year         = 1886 (January)\n| election_date     = {{start date|1884|12|03}}\n| image1            = [[file:George Murdoch ca 1866.jpg|150x150px]]\n| color1            = \n| candidate1        = [[George Murdoch]]\n| popular_vote1     = 202\n| percentage1       = 92.66%\n| image2            = <div style=\"width:150px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|AB|Independent Movement}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''E. R.'''</span></div>\n| color2            = \n| candidate2        = [[E. Redpath]]\n| popular_vote2     = 16\n| percentage2       = 7.34%\n| image3            = \n| candidate3        = \n| color3            = \n| popular_vote3     = \n| percentage3       = \n| map_image         = \n| map_size          = 350px\n| map_caption       = \n| title             = Mayor\n| before_election   = None\n| before_party      = \n| after_election    = [[George Murdoch]]\n| after_party       = \n}}\n\nThe '''1884 [[Calgary]] municipal election''' was held on December 3, 1884 to elect a [[List of mayors of Calgary|Mayor]] and four Councillors to sit on the first [[Calgary City Council|Calgary Town Council]] from December 4, 1884 to January 18, 1886 (Or possibly April 3, 1886, or possibly October 21, 1886).<ref name=\"1886CalHerald\">{{cite news |title=The Contest. Murdoch Elected to the Mayor's Chair. |url=http://peel.library.ualberta.ca/newspapers/CWH/1884/12/03/4/ |accessdate=8 March 2020 |work=The Calgary Herald |issue=14 |date=December 3, 1884 |page=4}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nCalgary was officially incorporated as ''Town of Calgary'' under provisions of the newly passed Northwest Territories ''Municipal Ordinance of 1884'' on November 17, 1884.<ref name=AMACityProfiles>{{cite web | url=http://www.municipalaffairs.alberta.ca/cfml/MunicipalProfiles/basicReport/CITY.PDF | publisher=[[Alberta Municipal Affairs]] | title=Location and History Profile: City of Calgary | page=15 | date=June 17, 2016 | accessdate=June 18, 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160325212924/http://www.municipalaffairs.alberta.ca/cfml/MunicipalProfiles/basicReport/CITY.PDF | archive-date=March 25, 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[Suffrage|Voting rights]] were provided to any male British subject over twenty-one years of age who are assessed on the last revised assessment roll with a minimum property value of $300.\n\nThe election was held under [[Multiple non-transferable vote]] where each elector was able to cast a ballot for the mayor and up to four ballots for separate councillors.<ref name=\"OrdMunicipal\">{{cite book |title=Ordinances of the North-West Territories |publisher=Queens Printer |location=Regina, Canada |edition=1884 |page=47-94 |url=https://contentdm.ucalgary.ca/digital/collection/p22007coll9/id/95263 |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Length of Council Term===\nThe first municipal council for the Town of Calgary was intended to sit from December 4, 1884 to January 18, 1886, however judicial interference by [[stipendiary magistrate]] [[Jeremiah Travis]] in the [[January 1886 Calgary municipal election|January 1886 election]] resulted in Territorial Ordinance 1-1886 \"''An Ordinance Respecting Municipal Matters in the Town of Calgary''\" voiding the results of the January 1886 election and declaring no council or mayor for the Town of Calgary exists.<ref>{{cite book |title=Ordinances of the Northwest Territories, Canada. |date=1886 |publisher=Regina : Government Printer |location=Regina, Canada |edition=1886 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011724067 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Calgary recognizes George Murdoch as Mayor of the Town of Calgary from December 4, 1884 to October 21, 1886, which implies the City either recognizes Murdoch as the winner of the January 1886 election, or recognizes Murdoch remained Mayor until the [[November 1886 Calgary municipal election|November 1886 election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Biographies of Calgary's Mayors |url=http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/cmayors.pdf |website=calgary.ca |publisher=The City of Calgary |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080411025822/http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/cmayors.pdf |archivedate=April 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n*The results of the elections, as reported in the December 3, 1884 edition of ''The Calgary Herald'', were as follows:\n===Mayor===\n{{Calgary municipal election, 1884/Position/Mayor}}\n\n===Councillors===\n{{Calgary municipal election, 1884/Position/Councillor}}\n\n==1885 Council By-election==\nSimon Jackson Hogg would resign from council effective May 20, 1885. A by-election was scheduled for June 17, 1885, and following nominations Isaac Sanford Freeze was acclaimed and installed June 10, 1885.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Frederick |title=THE MAYORS AND COUNCILS  OF  THE CORPORATION OF CALGARY |url=http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm |website=Roots Web |accessdate=14 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303003535/http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm |archivedate=March 3, 2020 |quote=Isaac Sanford Freeze, (1st Term), by-election for duration of unexpired one-year Term originally scheduled for 17 June 1885 but acclamation declared upon close of nominations 10 June 1885, sworn 10 June 1885, assumed Office 10 June 1885, Installation 10 June 1885}}</ref>\n\n==Also See==\n*[[List of Calgary municipal elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|1}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Frederick Hunter: [http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm THE MAYORS AND COUNCILS  OF  THE CORPORATION OF CALGARY] [https://web.archive.org/web/20200303003535/http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database/history/THE%20MAYORS%20AND%20COUNCILS%20OF%20THE%20CORPORATION%20OF%20CALGARY.htm Archived March 3, 2020]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calgary Municipal Election, 1884}}\n[[Category:Politics of Calgary]]\n[[Category:Municipal elections in Calgary]]\n[[Category:1884 elections in Canada]]\n[[Category:1880s in Calgary]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name     = 1884 Calgary municipal election\n| country           = Calgary\n| type              = Municipal\n| ongoing           = no\n| previous_election = <nowiki>None</nowiki>\n| previous_year     = <nowiki>None</nowiki>\n| next_election     = January 1886 Calgary municipal election\n| next_year         = 1886 (January)\n| election_date     = {{start date|1884|12|03}}\n| image1            = [[file:George Murdoch ca 1866.jpg|150x150px]]\n| color1            = \n| candidate1        = [[George Murdoch]]\n| popular_vote1     = 202\n| percentage1       = 92.66%\n| image2            = <div style=\"width:150px;\"><span style=\"line-height:150px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Canadian party colour|AB|Independent Movement}}; font-size:38px;\"> '''E. R.'''</span></div>\n| color2            = \n| candidate2        = [[E. Redpath]]\n| popular_vote2     = 16\n| percentage2       = 7.34%\n| image3            = \n| candidate3        = \n| color3            = \n| popular_vote3     = \n| percentage3       = \n| map_image         = \n| map_size          = 350px\n| map_caption       = \n| title             = Mayor\n| before_election   = None\n| before_party      = \n| after_election    = [[George Murdoch]]\n| after_party       = \n}}\n\nThe '''1884 [[Calg