, 1886, however judicial interference by [[stipendiary magistrate]] [[Jeremiah Travis]] in the [[January 1886 Calgary municipal election|January 1886 election]] resulted in Territorial Ordinance 1-1886 \"''An Ordinance Respecting Municipal Matters in the Town of Calgary''\" voiding the results of the January 1886 election and declaring no council or mayor for the Town of Calgary exists.<ref>{{cite book |title=Ordinances of the Northwest Territories, Canada. |date=1886 |publisher=Regina : Government Printer |location=Regina, Canada |edition=1886 |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011724067 |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Calgary recognizes George Murdoch as Mayor of the Town of Calgary from December 4, 1884 to October 21, 1886, which implies the City either recognizes Murdoch as the winner of the January 1886 election, or recognizes Murdoch remained Mayor until the [[November 1886 Calgary municipal election|November 1886 election]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Biographies of Calgary's Mayors |url=http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/cmayors.pdf |website=calgary.ca |publisher=The City of Calgary |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20080411025822/http://www.calgary.ca/DocGallery/BU/cityclerks/cmayors.pdf |archivedate=April 11, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n*The results of the elections, as reported in the December 3, 1884 edition of the ''The Calgary Herald'', were as follows:\n===Mayor===\n{{Calgary municipal election, 1884/Position/Mayor}}\n\n===Councillors===\n{{Calgary municipal election, 1884/Position/Councillor}}\n\n==1885 Council By-election==\nSimon Jackson Hogg would resign from council effective May 20, 1885. A by-election was scheduled for June 17, 1885, and following nominations Isaac Sanford Freeze was acclaimed and installed June 10, 1885.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hunter |first1=Frederick |title=THE MAYORS AND COUNCILS  OF  THE CORPORATION OF CALGARY |url=http://freepages.rootsweb.com/~database