2013, the media and marketing publication Digiday reported that Pornhub has already shown advertisements for various mainstream products on the Pornhub web site, including advertisements for movies, musical acts, anti-virus software, and a food delivery service, although most advertisements were still adult-related.<ref name=\"Digiday Mainstream Advertisers\">{{cite magazine|last1=Marshall|first1=Jack|title=How One Adult Site Attracts Mainstream Advertisers|url=http://digiday.com/publishers/pornhub-mainstream-advertisers/|magazine=[[Digiday]]|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413214330/http://digiday.com/publishers/pornhub-mainstream-advertisers/|archivedate=13 April 2014|date=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Malvertising===\nIt was reported in April 2013 that visitors to some of the world's most popular (by Alexa rank) pornography sites risked [[malware]] being installed on their machines by malicious third party advertisements.<ref name=\"BBC malware risk' to users\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Dave|title=Top porn sites 'pose growing malware risk' to users|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-22093141|website=BBC News|accessdate=6 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141125065546/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-22093141|archivedate=25 November 2014|date=12 April 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"The Independent porn websites 'host adverts with malware'\">{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Steve|title=Popular porn websites 'host adverts with malware'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/popular-porn-websites-host-adverts-with-malware-8568608.html|website=The Independent|accessdate=6 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141122182353/http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/popular-porn-websites-host-adverts-with-malware-8568608.html|archivedate=22 November 2014|date=11 April 2013}}</ref> The claims were made by security researcher<ref name=\"Conrad Longmoreis a security researcher\">{{cite web|last1=Cutlack|first1=Gary|title=Brave Researcher Visits Porn Sites and Discovers Shock Malware Risk|url=http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2013/04/brave-researcher-visits-porn-sites-and-discovers-shock-malware-risk/|website=Gizmodo UK|accessdate=6 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718194741/http://www.gizmodo.co.uk/2013/04/brave-researcher-visits-porn-sites-and-discovers-shock-malware-risk/|archivedate=18 July 2013|date=11 April 2013}}</ref> Conrad Longmore, who writes a blog on malware, spam and scams.<ref name=\"Dynamoo's Blog\">{{cite web|last1=Longmore|first1=Conrad|title=Dynamoo's Blog|url=http://blog.dynamoo.com/|website=Dynamoo's Blog. Malware, spam, scams and random stuff, by Conrad Longmore.|accessdate=6 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605210101/http://blog.dynamoo.com/|archivedate=5 June 2015|date=5 June 2015}}</ref> Longmore's figures were collected using [[Google Safe Browsing]] Diagnostics,<ref name=\"Conrad Longmore top porn sites lead to malware\">{{cite web|last1=Longmore|first1=Conrad|title=Top porn sites lead to malware|url=http://blog.dynamoo.com/2013/04/top-porn-sites-lead-to-malware.html|website=Dynamoo's Blog|accessdate=30 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903174255/http://blog.dynamoo.com/2013/04/top-porn-sites-lead-to-malware.html|archivedate=3 September 2014|date=9 April 2013}}</ref> which looks for harmful content on websites, and the statistics for two sites; [[xHamster]] and Pornhub were published by BBC News.<ref name=\"BBC malware risk' to users\" /> The BBC article stated that based on Longmore's research, 5% of pages on xHamster (which has never been owned by Mindgeek / Manwin), and 12.7% of pages on Pornhub incorporated [[malvertising]].<ref name=\"BBC malware risk' to users\" /> MindGeek (still known as Manwin at the time) said in a statement that their own figures showed that 0.003% of the advertisements they served over the period that Longmore's data was collected contained malware, and they said that the advertisements they serve are monitored for malware and malware is immediately removed.<ref name=\"BBC malware risk' to users\" />\n\nIn July 2013, Manwin announced that they had come to an agreement with the online security provider RiskIQ to scan third party advertisements hosted on their TrafficJunky ad network for malware before they go live, and to continue to monitor ads for malware once they are live.<ref name=\"XBIZ RiskIQ malware, TrafficJunky\" />\n\n==Age controls and child protection==\n\n===ASACP===\nMindgeek has been a Platinum Sponsor of ASACP ([[Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection]]) since 2011.<ref name=\"ASACP XBIZ June 2015\">{{cite web|title=ASACP Honors its Featured Sponsors for January, 2015|url=http://www.xbiz.com/news/189584|website=XBIZ.com|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614002959/http://www.xbiz.com/news/189584|archivedate=14 June 2015|date=5 January 2015}}</ref> ASACP is an American non-profit organization that fights against child pornography and aims to enhance the effectiveness of parental content filtering technology through the provision of the RTA (\"Restricted to Adults\") label, which can be implemented by webmasters of adult sites.<ref name=\"ASACP Homepage\">{{cite web|title=ASACP Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection|url=http://www.asacp.com/|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150315033339/http://www.asacp.com/|archivedate=15 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Age verification in the UK===\nIn March 2014 the UK video-on-demand co-regulator [[ATVOD]] requested a change in the law so that credit and debit card operators would be forbidden from processing payments from British customers of pornographic websites that did not carry out age checks before granting access. MindGeek responded in a statement: \"The best solution lies in a multi-layered approach in which the parent assumes the central role.\"<ref name=\"BBC Porn site age-check law demanded\">{{cite web|last1=Kelion|first1=Leo|title=Porn site age-check law demanded by media regulator|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-26779639|website=BBC News|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225093121/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-26779639|archivedate=25 February 2015|date=28 March 2014}}</ref> The UK's [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] won the country's [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] with a pledge to obligate UK internet service providers to block access to hardcore pornographic websites that did not implement age restrictions by using verifiable age checks.<ref name=\"Tories promise to enforce age limits\">{{cite web|title=Tories promise to enforce age limits on online pornography|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/04/tories-promise-to-enforce-age-limits-on-online-pornography|website=The Guardian|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613171810/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/04/tories-promise-to-enforce-age-limits-on-online-pornography|archivedate=13 June 2015|date=4 April 2015}}</ref> In light of this Mindgeek joined talks in May 2015 with the Digital Policy Alliance (DPA),<ref name=\"UK pornography industry proposes user ID checks\">{{cite web|last1=Gayle|first1=Damien|title=UK pornography industry proposes user ID checks for adult websites|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/may/26/pornography-industry-user-id-checks-adult-websites-privacy|website=The Guardian|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611135714/http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2015/may/26/pornography-industry-user-id-checks-adult-websites-privacy|archivedate=11 June 2015|date=26 May 2015}}</ref> an organisation that is funded by digital technology companies and informs members of parliament in the UK and the EU on policy issues that affect online and digital technologies.<ref name=\"Digital Policy Alliance - ABOUT US\">{{cite web|title=Digital Policy Alliance \u2013 ABOUT US|url=http://dpalliance.org.uk/about-us/|website=Digital Policy Alliance|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526020354/http://dpalliance.org.uk/about-us/|archivedate=26 May 2015}}</ref> The DPA has a working group to create [[Age verification system|age verification methods]] that could be used to comply with such laws.<ref name=\"Digital Policy Alliance - Age Verification Group\">{{cite web|title=Digital Policy Alliance \u2013 Age Verification Group|url=http://dpalliance.org.uk/age-verification-group/|website=Digital Policy Alliance|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150614005148/http://dpalliance.org.uk/age-verification-group/|archivedate=14 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Wired UK porn industry preps for mandatory ID checks\">{{cite web|last1=Collins|first1=Katie|title=UK porn industry preps for mandatory ID checks|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-05/26/uk-porn-industry-prepare-for-age-verification-legislation|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150526181400/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2015-05/26/uk-porn-industry-prepare-for-age-verification-legislation|archivedate=26 May 2015|date=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Digital Economy Act 2017]] introduced the relevant legislation, and in March 2018 MindGeek announced that its AgeID age-verification tool, which has been in use in Germany since 2015, would be made available in the UK in time for the proposed introduction of compulsory age-verification in April 2018. It was intended that the software would be made commercially available to all pornographic websites accessible within the UK, and offered free to independent UK studios, producers and bloggers. The software uses \"third-party age-verification companies\" to authenticate the age of those who register, after which they are able to access multiple sites across multiple devices without logging in again.<ref>{{cite news|title=Porn check critics fear data breach|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-43292457|date=6 March 2018|author=Zoe Kleinman|work=BBC News|access-date=7 March 2018}}</ref> Mindgeek was one of the leading private companies competing to provide an \nage-verification solution for the [[British Board of Film Classification]], the organisation designated as responsible for the age-verification process. The implementation date was originally April 2018 but was delayed to allow time for public consultation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Porn site age checks are delayed to make sure officials 'get it right'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/mar/12/porn-site-age-checks-delayed-government-gets-process-right|date=12 March 2018|author=Damien Gayle|work=BBC News|access-date=13 March 2018}}</ref> In May 2018 the [[Open Rights Group]], a UK-based digital rights campaigning organisation, criticized Mindgeek's record on data security and commented: \"Allowing pornographic sites to own and operate age verification tools leads to a conflict of interest between the privacy interests of the user, and the data-mining and market interests of the company.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= The government is acting negligently on privacy and porn AV|url=https://www.openrightsgroup.org/blog/2018/the-government-is-acting-negligently-on-privacy-and-porn-av|website=Open Rights Group|date=8 May 2018|author=Jim Killock|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref> In October 2019 the UK government abandoned their existing plans, instead proposing the introduction of an alternative regulatory system for the Internet.<ref name=Waterson2019-10-16>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2019/oct/16/uk-drops-plans-for-online-pornography-age-verification-system|title=UK drops plans for online pornography age verification system|last=Waterson |first=Jim|date=16 October 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=19 December 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Antitrust lawsuit against ICM and ICANN==\nManwin Licensing and Digital Playground filed an antitrust [[.xxx#Manwin suits|lawsuit]] in California in November 2011, against [[ICANN]] and [[ICM Registry]] over the introduction of the [[.xxx]] [[TLD]].<ref name=\"YouPorn sues ICANN and ICM over .xxx\">{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Kevin|title=YouPorn sues ICANN and ICM over .xxx|url=http://domainincite.com/6862-youporn-sues-icann-and-icm-over-xxx|website=DomainIncite|accessdate=20 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219062100/http://domainincite.com/6862-youporn-sues-icann-and-icm-over-xxx|archivedate=19 December 2014|date=16 November 2011}}</ref> Amongst their allegations, Manwin claimed that in introducing the new suffix, ICANN and ICM registry had exploited the market by making domain registrations expensive with no price caps in place, and created a need for defensive domain registrations with no provision for companies to block typos of their trademarks. Manwin announced that it would not allow its content to be used on any sites with the suffix, with Fabian Thylmann, who was then managing partner of Manwin saying: \"We oppose the .XXX domain and all it stands for. It is my opinion that .XXX domain is an anticompetitive business practice that works a disservice to all companies that do business on the Internet.\"<ref name=\"As .XXX Goes Live, ICANN Ushers in Virtual Red-Light District\">{{cite web|last1=Shayon|first1=Sheila|title=As .XXX Goes Live, ICANN Ushers in Virtual Red-Light District|url=http://www.brandchannel.com/home/post/2011/12/07/ICANN-Ushers-in-Virtual-Red-Light-District-120711.aspx|website=brandchannel|accessdate=20 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707081018/http://www.brandchannel.com/home/post/2011/12/07/ICANN-Ushers-in-Virtual-Red-Light-District-120711.aspx|archivedate=7 July 2012|date=7 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, ICM filed a counterclaim for $120 million against Manwin Licensing International. Part of the 24-page long claim alleged: \"Manwin, Digital Playground,  and their related companies,  affiliates, brands, and certain third party affiliates have conspired to boycott the .XXX TLD and have coerced and/or encouraged the boycott of .XXX websites by third parties.\"<ref name=\"The Domains ICM Operator of .XXX Counter Sues Manwin &\">{{cite web|last1=Berkens|first1=Michael|title=ICM Operator of .XXX Counter Sues Manwin & Digital Playground For $120 Million|url=http://www.thedomains.com/2012/10/01/iicm-operator-of-xxx-counter-sues-manwin-digital-playground-for-120-million/|website=The Domains|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219150550/http://www.thedomains.com/2012/10/01/iicm-operator-of-xxx-counter-sues-manwin-digital-playground-for-120-million/|archivedate=19 December 2013|date=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nAll of ICM's counterclaims were dismissed in the second half of February 2013. The judge in the case stated: \"Harm to ICM only is not sufficient to constitute antitrust injury. It must allege harm to the competitive process.\"<ref name=\"ICM\u2019s claims against Manwin thrown out of court\">{{cite web|last1=Murphy|first1=Kevin|title=ICM's claims against Manwin thrown out of court|url=http://domainincite.com/12011-icms-claims-against-manwin-thrown-out-of-court|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411095726/http://domainincite.com/12011-icms-claims-against-manwin-thrown-out-of-court|archivedate=11 April 2015|date=28 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Manwin agreed to settle the antitrust lawsuit it brought against ICM Registry over the cost of .xxx web domain names. The settlement will result in discounted wholesale prices of $7.85 a year for .xxx names during May 2013, and similar offers in the future.<ref name=\"Manwin, ICM Registry Settle Antitrust Lawsuit\">{{cite web|title=Manwin, ICM Registry Settle Antitrust Lawsuit|url=http://business.avn.com/articles/legal/Manwin-ICM-Registry-Settle-Antitrust-Lawsuit-515726.html|website=AVN|accessdate=20 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219060317/http://business.avn.com/articles/legal/Manwin-ICM-Registry-Settle-Antitrust-Lawsuit-515726.html|archivedate=19 December 2014|date=1 May 2013}}</ref> ICM Registry is owned by British former fax-machine mogul Stuart Lawley. The settlement provides that ICM will not pay any money directly to MindGeek.\n\n==Patent lawsuits==\nIn May 2013, ExitExchange Corp. sued Manwin USA Inc. in Texas, alleging that its patent for [[Pop-up ad#Pop-under ads|pop-under advertisements]] had been infringed by Tube8.com and Pornhub.com.<ref name=\"Patent Claims Over Pop-Under Ads\">{{cite web|last1=Pardon|first1=Rhett|title=7 Adult Companies Face Patent Claims Over Pop-Under Ads|url=http://www.xbiz.com/news/162715|website=XBIZ.com|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904004115/http://www.xbiz.com/news/162715|archivedate=4 September 2014|date=13 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, Manwin was sued by John Mikkelson and Robert Freidson, the operators of Skky Inc., in Minneapolis over the alleged infringement of a patent that describes a method for delivering compressed audio and images on mobile devices.<ref name=\"Adult Companies Sued Over Mobile Technology Patent\">{{cite web|last1=Pardon|first1=Rhett|title=Adult Companies Sued Over Mobile Technology Patent|url=http://www.xbiz.com/news/166908|website=XBIZ.com|accessdate=14 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131104223507/http://www.xbiz.com/news/166908|archivedate=4 November 2013|date=1 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2014, MindGeek USA Inc. was sued by Preservation Technologies LLC in Delaware for alleged infringement on 19 different sites operated by Mindgeek of 11 patent components on data distribution and communication systems, such as a system for cataloging and retrieving videos and other media associated with keywords.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pardon|first1=Rhett|title=MindGeek Targeted in Patent Infringement Suit |url=http://www.xbiz.com/news/189061|website=XBIX.com|accessdate=14 June 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218040317/http://www.xbiz.com/news/189061|archivedate=18 December 2014|date=17 December 2014}}</ref> The case was withdrawn in March 2015, after Mindgeek came to a settlement deal with Preservation Technologies LLC.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pardon|first1=Rhett|title=MindGeek Settles Data Management Patent Claim|url=http://www.xbiz.com/news/192151|accessdate=14 June 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329212934/http://www.xbiz.com/news/192151 |archivedate=29 March 2015 |date=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==No on Government Waste Committee==\nManwin was the biggest funder of the No on Government Waste Committee, which was supported by a coalition of entertainment companies, local business organizations, community activists, adult entertainment performers and healthcare advocates.\" The committee ran the No on [[Measure B]] campaign.<ref>{{cite web | title = No on Measure B | url = http://www.noongovernmentwaste.com/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121022052248/http://www.noongovernmentwaste.com/ | archive-date = 22 October 2012 | publisher = No on Government Waste Committee | quote = DISCLAIMER: Paid for by the No on Government Waste Committee. Major Funding by Manwin USA. }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Romero | first = Dennis | title = Fabian Thylmann, porn King opposing condoms in L.A. adult video, arrested | url = http://www.laweekly.com/news/fabian-thylmann-porn-king-opposing-condoms-in-la-adult-video-arrested-2386412 | work = LA Weekly | publisher = Voice Media Group | date = 11 December 2012 }}</ref> The No on Measure B campaign was supported by the Los Angeles County Federation of [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] Women, Los Angeles County Republican and [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] Parties, the [[Valley Industry & Commerce Association]] (VICA), and the [[Log Cabin Republicans]] of Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news |last= Kernes |first= Mark |title=Log Cabin Republicans of Los Angeles announce opposition to Measure B, Says No on Government Waste Committee |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/log-cabin-republicans-los-angeles-150000501.html |location= |work=Yahoo! Finance |publisher=No on Government Waste Committee | date = 20 September 2012  |accessdate= 9 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite news |title=L'\u00e9nigme Mindgeek, Du Luxembourg \u00c0 Montr\u00e9al |url= http://plus.lapresse.ca/screens/5af271ce-5112-411d-8502-319e5d5fa7e7__7C__2tXW0KGJgOr7.html|last=Bergeron |first=Maxime |date=10 October 2016 |newspaper=La Presse |language=French|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web|title=\u041a\u0442\u043e \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043b PornHub, Brazzers \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0443\u0447\u0438\u043b \u043c\u0438\u0440 \u043a \u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438|url=https://lenta.ru/themes/2017/09/07/mindgeek/|date=7 September 2017|website=Lenta.ru|language=Russian|access-date=}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.mindgeek.com/}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100925120314/http://www.manwin.com:80/ |date=25 September 2010 |title=Manwin website }}\n** {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080703154126/http://www.mansef.com/ |date=3 July 2008 |title=Mansef website }}\n* [https://wiki.openrightsgroup.org/wiki/MindGeek MindGeek at Open Rights Group wiki] - [[Open Rights Group]]\n* {{Crunchbase|mindgeek}}\n* {{OpenCorp|Mindgeek|Mindgeek}}\n* [http://banquecarrefour.blogspot.com/2016/12/who-is-behind-youporn-mindgeek-manwin.html Companies behind MindGeek]\n\n{{Manwin}}\n\n{{Coord|45|29|50.0|N|73|39|23.4|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:MindGeek]]\n[[Category:Adult entertainment companies]]\n[[Category:Pornhub Network]]\