&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|orig-year = 1976|ref=harv}}\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:James Bond in film]]\n[[Category:Lists of films by source]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Bond films themselves|the production background of the films|Production of the James Bond films|the various portrayals of the character|Portrayal of James Bond in film}}\n{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2016}}\n\n[[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]] is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] created by the novelist [[Ian Fleming]] in 1953. Bond is a British secret agent working for [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] who also answers to his codename, 007. He has been [[James Bond filmography|portrayed on film]] by the actors [[Sean Connery]], [[David Niven]], [[George Lazenby]], [[Roger Moore]], [[Timothy Dalton]], [[Pierce Brosnan]], and [[Daniel Craig]], in twenty-seven productions. All the films but two were made by [[Eon Productions]]. Eon now holds the full adaptation rights to all of [[James Bond novels|Fleming's Bond novels]].<ref name=\"Poliakoff\" /><ref name=\"Shprintz:Variety\" />\n\nIn 1961 the producers [[Albert R. Broccoli]] and [[Harry Saltzman]] joined forces to purchase the filming rights to Fleming's novels.{{sfn|Chapman|2009|p=5}} They founded the production company Eon Productions and, with financial backing by [[United Artists]], began working on ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'', which was directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] and featured Connery as Bond.{{sfn|Chapman|2009|p=43}} Following ''Dr. No''{{'}}s release in 1962, Broccoli and Saltzman created the holding company [[Danjaq]] to ensure future productions in the [[James Bond in film|''James Bond'' film series]].<ref name=\"Danjaq v Sony\" /> The series currently encompasses twenty-four films, with the most recent, ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'', released in October 2015. With a combined gross of nearly $7&nbsp;billion to date, the films produced by Eon constitute the [[List of highest-grossing film series|fourth-highest-grossing film series]], behind the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]], ''[[Star Wars]]'' and [[Wizarding World]] films.<ref name=\"Numbers franchises\" /> Accounting for the effects of [[inflation]], the Bond films have amassed over $14&nbsp;billion at current prices.{{efn|Prior to the release of ''Skyfall'' in 2012, the James Bond series had grossed approximately $12.5&nbsp;billion at 2011 prices;<ref name=\"economist\"/> after factoring in earnings of almost $2&nbsp;billion from ''Skyfall'' and ''Spectre'', the series has earned at least $14&nbsp;billion adjusted for inflation.}} The films have won five [[Academy Awards]]: for [[Academy Award for Sound Editing|Sound Effects]] (now Sound Editing) in ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' ([[37th Academy Awards|at the 37th Awards]]), to [[John Stears]] for [[Academy Award for Visual Effects|Visual Effects]] in ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' ([[38th Academy Awards|at the 38th Awards]]), to [[Per Hallberg]] and [[Karen Baker Landers]] for [[Academy Award for Sound Editing|Sound Editing]], to [[Adele]] and [[Paul Epworth]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Original Song]] in ''Skyfall'' ([[85th Academy Awards|at the 85th Awards]]), and to [[Sam Smith (singer)|Sam Smith]] and [[Jimmy Napes]] for Original Song in ''[[Spectre (2015 film)|Spectre]]'' ([[88th Academy Awards|at the 88th Awards]]). Additionally, several of the songs produced for the films have been nominated for Academy Awards for Original Song, including [[Paul McCartney]]'s \"[[Live and Let Die (song)|Live and Let Die]]\", [[Carly Simon]]'s \"[[Nobody Does It Better]]\" and [[Sheena Easton]]'s \"[[For Your Eyes Only (Sheena Easton song)|For Your Eyes Only]]\". In 1982 Albert R. Broccoli received the [[Irving G. Thalberg Memorial Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1982|title=The 54th Academy Awards (1982)|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]] (AMPAS)|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nWhen Broccoli and Saltzman bought the rights to existing and future Fleming titles, it did not include ''[[Casino Royale (novel)|Casino Royale]]'', which had already been sold to producer [[Gregory Ratoff]], with the story having been [[Casino Royale (Climax!)|adapted for television]] in 1954. After Ratoff's death, the rights were passed on to [[Charles K. Feldman]],{{sfn|Balio|1987|p=255}} who subsequently produced the satirical Bond spoof ''[[Casino Royale (1967 film)|Casino Royale]]'' in 1967.<ref name=\"CR: MGM\" /> A legal case ensured that the film rights to the novel [[Thunderball (novel)|''Thunderball'']] were held by [[Kevin McClory]] as he, Fleming and the screenwriter [[Jack Whittingham]] had written a film script upon which the novel was based.<ref name=\"Poliakoff\" /> Although Eon Productions and McClory joined forces to produce ''Thunderball'', McClory still retained the rights to the story and adapted ''Thunderball'' into 1983's ''[[Never Say Never Again]]''.<ref name=\"lost\" /> The current distribution rights to both of those films are held by [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures]], the studio which distributes Eon's regular series.<ref name=\"MGM acq\" /><ref name=\"NYT: Sony & MGM\" />\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Eon films==\nThe Eon-produced films have a combined gross of nearly $7 billion, and constitute the [[List of highest-grossing film series|sixth-highest-grossing film series]].<ref name=\"Numbers franchises\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!rowspan=\"2\" scope=col|Title\n!rowspan=\"2\" scope=col|Year\n!rowspan=\"2\" scope=col|Bond actor\n!rowspan=\"2\" scope=col|Director\n! colspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Box office (millions){{sfn|Block|Autrey Wilson|2010|pp=428\u2013429}}\n! colspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\" | Budget (millions){{sfn|Block|Autrey Wilson|2010|pp=4